          "body": "Verses 15-16 close the chapter with a softer, more pastoral note. Eating a naturally dead animal (*nevelah*) or one torn by beasts (*terephah*) is not a *karat* offense — it results in temporary, remediable impurity. The person washes their clothes, bathes, remains unclean until evening, then is clean. Neglect of the washing, however, incurs guilt (*avon*, v. 16). The distinction matters: the graduated response shows that the chapter is not painting all violations with the same brush. Deliberate blood-eating incurs divine opposition and covenantal excision; accidental contact with blood through carrion incurs ritual impurity that a structured purification rite resolves by sundown. The Levitical system has room for weakness and inadvertence — it is the defiant, willful transgression that earns the severest penalties. The chapter ends, as Leviticus characteristically does, not with condemnation but with a path back."
