        "title": "Centralized slaughter — redirecting Israel's worship instinct from the field to the altar",
        "range": "17:1-7",
        "excerpt": "Any man from the house of Israel who slaughters an ox or a lamb or a goat in the camp, or who slaughters it outside the camp, and has not brought it to the doorway of the tent of meeting to present it as an offering to the Lord... bloodguiltiness is to be reckoned to that man.",
        "body": "Verses 3-7 address a concrete crisis, not a hypothetical danger. Verse 7 reveals what was already happening: the sons of Israel were 'sacrificing their sacrifices to the goat demons with which they play the harlot.' The law is responsive, not merely preventive. The goat demons (*sairim*) were wilderness entities in the religious imagination of the ancient Near East — goat-like or hairy beings associated with liminal spaces and wild territories. Leviticus 16:8-10 had just made the scapegoat's destination 'Azazel' — a wilderness entity — establishing the wilderness as spiritually dangerous territory. Chapter 17 now regulates the danger by eliminating every legitimate reason to slaughter an animal outside the tabernacle's orbit.\n\nThe law's positive strategy is its most significant feature. Every domestic animal slaughter — even for food — was, under these wilderness conditions, to become a peace offering (*zevach shelamim*) at the tabernacle (v. 5). This is not a universal permanent dietary law requiring sacrifice before every meal (Deuteronomy 12:15-25 explicitly relaxes this provision for non-sacrificial killing once Israel enters the land and the tabernacle is far from many settlements). It is a contextually bounded, strategically total regulation for the wilderness period, when the tabernacle was accessible to all and when syncretistic worship was an immediate threat. The aim is stated plainly in verse 5: 'so that the sons of Israel may bring their sacrifices which they were sacrificing in the open field, that they may bring them in to the LORD.'\n\nThe penalty — 'bloodguiltiness... that man shall be cut off' (v. 4) — seems disproportionate until its logic is grasped. Slaughtering an animal outside the altar was not just unauthorized; it was the functional equivalent of murder. The animal's blood, which belongs on the altar to atone, is shed outside the system that gives shedding blood its meaning. The man who slaughters privately has shed blood without making atonement with it — and the chapter's central claim (v. 11) is that blood's only legitimate function is atoning. Private slaughter without the altar wastes the atoning substance, and in doing so it incurs the same guilt as wasting a human life.\n\nThe 'permanent statute throughout their generations' (*chuqqah olam ledorotam*, v. 7) is attached not to the specific peace-offering requirement but to the anti-demonic prohibition: no more sacrificing to *sairim*. This narrowing confirms that the specific mechanism (every animal to the tabernacle) was contextual, while the theological principle (no worship outside the LORD's appointed system) is permanent. The Reformed tradition has consistently applied this principle to worship generally: what is not commanded in God's appointed mode of approach is not permitted — a principle Calvin called the *regulative principle* of worship.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Sair* (goat demon, v. 7) appears in Isaiah 13:21 and 34:14 as a wilderness being. *Zanah* (to play the harlot, v. 7) is the covenant-infidelity verb — used throughout the prophets (Hosea 1:2; Ezekiel 16) for Israel's idolatry as adultery against God. *Shelem* (peace offering) carries the root *shalom* — wholeness, completion; the offering that restores and maintains the relational integrity between God and the worshiper."
