        "range": "17:8-9",
        "excerpt": "Any man from the house of Israel, or from the aliens who sojourn among them, who offers a burnt offering or sacrifice, and does not bring it to the doorway of the tent of meeting to offer it to the Lord, that man also shall be cut off from his people.",
        "body": "Verses 8-9 extend the centralization principle from domestic slaughter to formal sacrifice. Burnt offerings (*olah*) and other sacrifices offered anywhere other than the tent of meeting incur the same *karat* penalty as unauthorized slaughter. The statute is brief but its inclusion of the resident alien (*ger*) is theologically momentous.\n\nThe *ger* in ancient Israel occupied a liminal social position — not an Israelite by birth, not a foreigner passing through, but a resident who had settled within the community and was under its social protection and its legal jurisdiction. The Torah's inclusion of the *ger* in blood-law and sacrifice-law is one of the most radical features of Mosaic legislation in its ancient Near Eastern context. Surrounding legal codes defined obligations by ethnic and class status; Leviticus 17 defines them by proximity to the covenant community and its altar. The alien who lives among Israel comes under the altar's claim — and the altar's provision. He may bring a burnt offering (v. 8); he may also approach the one God who atones.\n\nThis inclusion is not incidental. It establishes the theological principle that the altar's jurisdiction is spatial and relational, not racial. The New Testament will carry this logic to its conclusion in Ephesians 2:11-13, where Gentiles who were 'strangers to the covenants of promise' are now brought near 'by the blood of Christ.' The *ger* of Leviticus is the type; the believing Gentile is the antitype. Peter Davids, in his work on the epistle of James, notes that the New Testament's consistent application of Old Testament holiness language to Gentile believers presupposes exactly this inclusive logic already present in the Mosaic law."
