        "number": 5,
        "title": "Hunting, carrion, and the sanctity of all creaturely life",
        "range": "17:13-16",
        "excerpt": "So when any man from the sons of Israel, or from the aliens who sojourn among them, in hunting catches a beast or a bird which may be eaten, he shall pour out its blood and cover it with earth.",
        "body": "Verses 13-16 extend the blood-legislation to two cases outside the altar context: lawful hunting (v. 13) and accidental eating of carrion or prey (vv. 15-16). Both cases address situations where the altar mechanism is not available — the hunter in the field, the traveler who finds a dead animal. In both cases, the blood-theology of verse 11 continues to govern even when sacrifice is impossible.\n\nThe hunting regulation (v. 13) is the most culturally significant. Domesticated animals could be brought to the tabernacle; wild game taken in the field cannot. The law therefore provides an alternative rite: pour the blood on the ground and cover it with earth. The act is deliberate and reverential — the blood is not ignored or wasted; it is deliberately handled, returned to the ground from which the animal came. Gordon Wenham (*The Book of Leviticus*, NICOT) suggests the covering-with-earth gesture is the functional equivalent of 'returning' the life to God — acknowledging in the act of covering that the blood belongs to the One who gave the life. The hunter who skins his catch and throws the blood aside as inconvenient has violated the same principle as the blood-eater; the hunter who pours and covers has honored the theological reality even without an altar.\n\nThe carrion regulation (vv. 15-16) introduces graduated defilement. Eating a *nevelah* (naturally dead animal) or a *terephah* (torn-by-beast animal) was not *karat*-level; it was temporary impurity requiring washing and waiting until evening. The penalty calibration is instructive: the deliberate, willful eating of blood is a capital covenant offense (vv. 10, 14); the accidental or need-driven eating of carrion is a ritual impurity that purification rites resolve. The legal system distinguishes between high-handed rebellion against the atoning structure and weakness or inadvertence within it. The person who eats carrion in desperation and then washes is clean by evening; the person who eats blood willfully faces God's face set against them.\n\nTogether these closing verses show that the chapter's concern is not merely liturgical but cosmic — the sanctity of animal life and its blood is not confined to the altar precinct. Every creature's blood belongs to God because every creature's life belongs to God. The hunter in the field and the traveler who finds a carcass are both acting within a universe in which the creator has specified that life is sacred and blood is not food. The command to cover the blood with earth is one of the quieter gestures in the Torah, but it enacts in a single physical act the theology the whole chapter has been building: life comes from God, returns to God, and is not available for human consumption.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nevelah* (v. 15) — a carcass, an animal that has died of natural causes; later Mishnaic Hebrew extends the term. *Terephah* (v. 15) — literally 'torn,' prey killed by wild beasts. *Avon* (guilt/iniquity, v. 16) — a weightier moral term than mere uncleanness; the person who fails to wash bears *avon*, not merely *tum'ah* (impurity). *Aphar* (earth/dust, v. 13) — the same word as Genesis 2:7 ('formed man from the dust'). Covering blood with earth returns it, symbolically, to its origin."
